It is laid out in a 16x16 format, so it is easier to select all cells at once. Generally, MAF Scaling should apply to the entire table in percentages. The stock curve fits a 3rd order polynomial which is the correct shape for a MAF. So it is best to retain that shape by only multiplying all cells by the same values and make any other changes to your main Fuel Map. !!! Low RPM Threshold
The ECU runs through a section of code to check for TPS and/or MAF plausibility to detect sensor errors that aren't due to simple disconnects. The ECU has a rough Alpha N map that knows how RPM, TPS, and MAF should relate to one another. If sensor readings fall outside of this range, it will throw a code for plausibility. For example, at 25% Throttle at 3400RPM, you can have a situation where the turbo has spooled up and is generating a lot of airflow. This would never happen in an NA engine so the ECU sees this extra air read by the MAF sensor and thinks something is wrong. But it only checks for this in a narrow window of RPM between 1504 and 3488 and TPS between 13% and 30% in stock form. We can change these thresholds to fool the ECU into never running this code by changing the RPM thresholds.

For example, at 25% Throttle at 3400RPM, you can have a situation where the turbo has spooled up and is generating a lot of airflow. Low RPM Threshold
The ECU runs through a section of code to check for TPS and/or MAF plausibility to detect sensor errors that aren't due to simple disconnects. The ECU has a rough Alpha N map that knows how RPM, TPS, and MAF should relate to one another. If sensor readings fall outside of this range, it will throw a code for plausibility. For example, at 25% Throttle at 3400RPM, you can have a situation where the turbo has spooled up and is generating a lot of airflow. This would never happen in an NA engine so the ECU sees this extra air read by the MAF sensor and thinks something is wrong. But it only checks for this in a narrow window of RPM between 1504 and 3488 and TPS between 13% and 30% in stock form. We can change these thresholds to fool the ECU into never running this code by changing the RPM thresholds.

ip_fac_is_ivvt__tco__tco_st. Engine coolant temperature blending factor for transition from tco_1_is to tco_2_is during idle. Used to blend injection and ignition tables. Set all cells to 1 to only use the Cold idle injection and ignition tables
ip_fac_pl_ivvt__tco__tco_st. Engine coolant temperature blending factor for transition from tco_1 to tco_2 during part and full load. Used to blend injection and ignition tables. Set all cells to 1 to only use the Cold part load injection and ignition tables
ip_fac_cam_sp_in_is__tco__tco_st. Engine coolant temperature blending factor for transition from cam_sp_tco1 to cam_sp_tco2 during idle. Intake camshaft. Set all cells to 1 to only use the Cold intake vanos idle tables
ip_fac_cam_sp_in_ex__tco__tco_st. Engine coolant temperature blending factor for transition from cam_sp_tco1 to cam_sp_tco2 during idle. Exhaust camshaft. Set all cells to 1 to only use the Cold exhaust vanos idle tables
ip_fac_cam_sp_in_pl__tco__tco_st. Engine coolant temperature blending factor for transition from cam_sp_tco1 to cam_sp_tco2 during part and full load. Intake camshaft Set all cells to 1 to only use the Cold intake vanos part throttle tables
ip_fac_cam_sp_ex_pl__tco__tco_st. Engine coolant temperature blending factor for transition from cam_sp_tco1 to cam_sp_tco2 during part and full load. Exhaust camshaft Set all cells to 1 to only use the Cold exhaust vanos part throttle tables
